A. Changing the Legal Landscape President Ronald Reagan and Congress passed a series of sweeping changes in the Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984, described as “the most significant series of changes in the federal criminal justice system ever enacted at one time.”84 The CCCA created new federal crimes and mandatory minimum sentences, increased fines and sentences for federal offenses, expanded asset forfeiture, and treated juvenile crime more harshly.85 In the Bail Reform Act of 1984,86 one part of the CCCA, Congress expanded the availability of pretrial detention.87 Congress allowed courts to consider a defendant’s risk of danger to the community and did not limit its notion of “danger” to possible violent crimes; instead, Congress expressly contemplated detaining defendants so that they would not engage in drug trafficking, an activity that “constitutes a danger to the safety of any other person or the community.”88 Indeed, the Act created a rebuttable presumption that a defendant is dangerous (and therefore should be detained) if he is charged with a drug violation that carries a maximum penalty of at least ten years.89 Individuals charged with a drug felony that involved the use or possession of a firearm were also presumed to be dangerous.90 The goal of the bail reform

